Components Should Render, Not Think
One of the biggest architectural mistakes in Angular projects is allowing components to become responsible for everything.
A component starts by displaying data.
A few weeks later it validates permissions.
Then it calculates discounts.
Then it decides which API to call.
Then it coordinates multiple services.
Before long, the component has become the feature.
The UI is now tightly coupled to business logic.
A Common Example
Many Angular components eventually look like this:
saveCustomer() {
if (!this.permissions.canEdit()) {
return;
}if (!this.customer.isVerified) {
return;
}
if (this.customer.balance > 1000) {
this.customerService.sendForApproval(this.customer);
} else {
this.customerService.save(this.customer);
}
}
It works.
